Jan- 1st,, 1867
Another year begins today. It is my wish to spend it more to the service of God and to my own improvement than the last one was. The day was spent in writing and other employments and one would not know from anything going on, that it was "Happy New Year". 2nd  The Crows are in a quandary about the Sioux. They have received orders from them to leave our vicinity and they are afraid to disobey, and yet would like to remain and help the whites. 3rd The Colonel is making arrangements with "Iron Bull" and a few other indians to stay as spies and scouts.

Jan 7th Two indians went out as scouts this morning and in the afternoon came back accompanied by six or eight Crows who belonged to a party that went from the Crow Village to join the other band. They were on their way to the village, and stopped here over night. The report now is that the Sioux are encamped on the Big Horn near the month and are on their way up. "Lone Horn" "The Roman Nose" Sioux Chiefs were in the Crow Camp a few days before they moved and told the Crows that they were friendly to the whites and are going to leave the other Sioux and would join the Crows next spring and his with them. Jan 4 The indians raised camp early and moved to the river bank first above the Fort, intending to cross the river in the morning and move over towards Wind River valley. A great many came up to camp as they came by. Jan 5th Indians moved early. "Iron Bull" wouldn't stay, but "Annahare". "The Black Eagle" and three or four others remained. Jan 6th "Shot in the face" a chief of some importance remained behind and this morning moved up to camp and pitched his lodge. Crow chiefs to come up and tell the whites to fortify as the Sioux to the number of several thousands would be here in a week or so.
Jan 8th Great preparations have been in progress for some time strengthening the fort, and preparing for a seige. 
Jan 9th Hauled up a lot of ice intending to use it for water in case we are hemmed in.
Jan 10 Snowing again.

"    11 Ditto. The scouts report plenty of buffalo on the road to Phil Kearney, but say they are not moving. If they were moving this way it would be a sign that the mail was coming.
